Supplemental Information

SI Figure 1: Allometric mass function using values for Atlantic cod and juvenile and adult pollock from Fish Bioenergetics 4 and the values for hake from Francis (1983) where CA = 0.167 and CA/2 = 0.0835.

SI Figure 2: Temperature-dependent consumption rate function using values for Atlantic cod and pollock from Fish Bioenergetics 4 and the estimates for hake. Optimal and maximum temperatures for hake are modelled for the entire acoustic survey area and for kriged, grided temperatures where hake were present.

SI Figure 3: Yearly mean kriged temperatures overall, mean kriged temperatures weighted by hake biomass estimate for that grid, mean survey temperatures, and mean ROMS output for the summer months (June to September).

SI Figure 4: Age vs.length from the lake assessment, the values assigned to CCTD predators and prey (with bounds of 1 and 15 for CEATTLE), and ages from FEAT acoustic-trawl survey data

SI Figure 5: Dirichlet reweighting output for calculation of mean diet proportion from all records of hake depredation by predator age (box) and prey age (column). Black bars represent 95% confidence interval.

SI Figure 6: Simplified diet proportion for sensitivity testing with rations of maximum 0.5%, 10%, 50%, and 80% cannibalism, compared to the mean cannibalism derived from the empirical data

SI Figure 7: Dirichlet reweighting output for calculation of mean diet proportion from records of hake depredation in years 1988-1999 by predator age (box) and prey age (column). Black bars represent 95% confidence interval.

SI Figure 8: Dirichlet reweighting output for calculation of mean diet proportion from records of hake depredation in years 2005-2019 by predator age (box) and prey age (column). Black bars represent 95% confidence interval.

SI Figure 9: Top hake prey by occurrence and weight in hake stomachs within the CCTD.
